Hm, I couldn't find a test where the loop doesn't start from the first point. So the solution without a dictionary also passes all the tests:

...
    auto start = make_tuple(x, y, vx, vy);
    int crashed = 0;
    bool cycled = false;
    for (int i = 0; i < time; ++i) {
        if (i && !cycled) {
            if (start == make_tuple(x, y, vx, vy)) {
                i += (time - i) / i * i;
                cycled = true;
            }
        }
...

Ah, I think it could be easier. For each state (x, y, vx, vy) we can exactly restore previous state:
vx += Math.Sign(x);
vy += Math.Sign(y);
x -= vx;
y -= vy;
If we find a cycle not through the start point it means that a current state has more than one previous state.
